    86	
    87	## Authoritative Target Chunk Schema (spectra_data.parquet, chunked mode)
    88	
    89	Exact reference Arrow schema [VERIFIED: pyarrow dump of `small.chunked.mzpeak`]:
    90	
    91	```
    92	chunk: struct<
    93	  spectrum_index:  uint64,
    94	  mz_chunk_start:  double,
    95	  mz_chunk_end:    double,
    96	  mz_chunk_values: large_list<item: double>,   # item NULLABLE
    97	  chunk_encoding:  string,                       # CURIE value "MS:1003089"
    98	  intensity:       large_list<item: float>       # item NULLABLE, f32
    99	>
   100	```
   101	
   102	**Exactly 6 fields. NO `mz_numpress_linear_bytes` in delta mode.** [VERIFIED: `st.num_fields == 6`; Rust `ChunkingStrategy::Delta::extra_arrays() -> vec![]`]
   103	
   104	Per-field metadata in the reference (each field carries Arrow field metadata; the planner should attach the equivalent in the footer `spectrum_array_index`, see §array_index — Parquet.Net does not need to set Arrow field-level metadata since the v1 writer already relies on the footer JSON, not Arrow field metadata, to pass the validator):
   105	
   106	| Field | array_accession | data_type_accession | buffer_format | transform | unit | sorting_rank |
   107	|-------|-----------------|---------------------|---------------|-----------|------|--------------|
   108	| mz_chunk_start | MS:1000514 | MS:1000523 | chunk_start | MS:1003901 | MS:1000040 | 0 |
   109	| mz_chunk_end | MS:1000514 | MS:1000523 | chunk_end | MS:1003901 | MS:1000040 | 0 |
   110	| mz_chunk_values | MS:1000514 | MS:1000523 | chunk_values | MS:1003901 | MS:1000040 | 0 |
   111	| chunk_encoding | MS:1000514 | MS:1000523 | chunk_encoding | MS:1003901 | MS:1000040 | 0 |
   112	| intensity | MS:1000515 | MS:1000521 | chunk_secondary | MS:1003902 | MS:1000131 | (null) |
   113	
   114	**Parquet.Net schema declaration (planner copies this shape):**
   115	```csharp
   116	new StructField("chunk",
   117	    new DataField<ulong>("spectrum_index"),
   118	    new DataField<double>("mz_chunk_start"),
   119	    new DataField<double>("mz_chunk_end"),
   120	    new ListField("mz_chunk_values", new DataField<double>("item", true)),  // nullable item
   121	    new DataField<string>("chunk_encoding"),
   122	    new ListField("intensity", new DataField<float>("item", true)));         // nullable item
   123	```
   124	
   125	**large_list vs list:** Parquet.Net 5.0.1 emits a 32-bit-offset `list`, the reference uses `large_list` (64-bit offsets). This is the **same accepted deviation already shipped in v1** for `large_string`/`large_list` metadata fields. The mzPeak Python reader and `mzpeak-validate` read both transparently (the validator's chunk check only asserts a top-level `chunk` column exists). [VERIFIED: validator structural rule `data_kind_has_facet` checks `tops & {"point","chunk"}`; v1 already passes with plain list/string]
   126	
   127	### spectra_peaks stays POINT layout (do NOT chunk it)
   128	[VERIFIED: pyarrow dump — `spectra_peaks.parquet` in the chunked archive is `point: struct<spectrum_index:uint64, mz:double, intensity:float>`, identical to v1.] The existing `PointFacetStream` for peaks is unchanged.
   129	
   130	## Delta Encoding (exact algorithm + worked example)
   131	
   132	### Decisions
   133	- **`chunk_encoding` value = `"MS:1003089"`** (the DELTA_ENCODE CURIE), stored as a plain `string` column. NOT `"delta"`. [VERIFIED: pyarrow + `src/chunk_series.rs:56`]
   134	- **`mz_chunk_start` / `mz_chunk_end` = first / last NON-NULL actual m/z in the window** (actual extent, not window boundary). [VERIFIED: `encode_arrow` takes `it.next()` / `it.next_back()` over non-null values]
   135	- **`mz_chunk_values` is null-aware delta-encoded** and does **NOT** include the start value as its first element. The start value lives in `mz_chunk_start` only. [VERIFIED: `null_delta_encode` + `ChunkingStrategy::Delta` arm]
   136	- **Lossless requirement met** by reproducing the v1 point multiset exactly — proven 14/14 below. [VERIFIED in session]
   137	
   138	### Encode algorithm (mirror of `null_delta_encode`, `src/filter.rs:788`)
   139	Input: the window's m/z slice `mz[0..k]` and intensity slice `int[0..k]`, AFTER `nullify_zero_intensity` has set both `mz[i]` and `int[i]` to **null** wherever `is_zero_pair_mask` is true (a zero intensity whose previous OR next intensity is also zero — i.e. interior of a zero-run; flanking single zeros are kept).
   140	
   141	`mz_chunk_start = first non-null mz`, `mz_chunk_end  = last non-null mz`.
   142	
   143	`mz_chunk_values` (length == k, one element per point INCLUDING nulls, but the first element is dropped per the delta rule below):
   144	
   145	```
   146	buffer = []
   147	it = iter(mz)            # mz is the (nullified) window slice
   148	last = it.next()         # first element
   149	if last is None: buffer.append(None)     # leading null kept as a marker
   150	for item in it:          # remaining elements
   151	    if item is not None:
   152	        if last is not None:
   153	            buffer.append(item - last)   # delta
   154	            last = item
   155	        else:
   156	            buffer.append(item)          # ABSOLUTE (previous was null → store raw m/z)
   157	            last = item
   158	    else:
   159	        buffer.append(None)              # null marker
   160	        last = None
   161	return buffer            # length == len(mz) - 1  (+1 if a leading null was appended)
   162	```
   163	Key rule: **after a null, the next real value is stored ABSOLUTE (raw m/z), not as a delta.** That is why row 1+ in the dump shows `[None, 252.965..., 0.0003874..., ...]` — the `252.965` is an absolute restart, then deltas resume.
   164	
   165	`intensity` list = the (nullified) intensity slice verbatim (nullable f32 items). Its length == k.
   166	
   167	### Decode algorithm (mirror of `null_delta_decode`, `src/filter.rs:826`) — VERIFIED CORRECT
   168	```python
   169	def null_delta_decode(arr, start):   # arr = mz_chunk_values, start = mz_chunk_start
   170	    buf = []; last = start
   171	    if arr[0] is None:
   172	        if len(arr) > 1 and arr[1] is None:
   173	            buf.append(last)        # singleton peak exactly at the chunk boundary
   174	        last = None
   175	    else:
   176	        buf.append(start)           # start is the FIRST reconstructed m/z
   177	    for item in arr:
   178	        if item is not None:
   179	            if last is not None:
   180	                d = item + last; buf.append(d); last = d   # cumulative delta
   181	            else:
   182	                buf.append(item); last = item               # absolute restart
   183	        else:
   184	            buf.append(None); last = None
   185	    return buf                       # decoded m/z (length == len(intensity)), nulls aligned
   186	```
   187	Reconstructed `(mz, intensity)` = `zip(decoded_mz, intensity)`, **dropping pairs where either is null** (those are the nullified interior-zero points the reader treats as absent).
   188	
   189	### Worked example (row 1, spectrum 0, from the actual file)
   190	```
   191	mz_chunk_start = 252.96545361882283
   192	mz_chunk_values[:6] = [None, 252.96545361882283, 0.00038742706865946275, 0.00038742825540794, ...]
   193	intensity[:6]       = [None, 1328.2458, 3272.7817, 4725.3662, ...]
   194	```
   195	Decode:
   196	- `arr[0] is None` and `arr[1]` is NOT None → do not push start; set `last=None`.
   197	- iterate: `None` → push None (last=None). `252.965...` (last is None) → push **252.96545361882283** absolute (last=252.965). `0.000387427...` (last set) → push `252.96545361882283 + 0.00038742706865946275 = 252.96584104589149` (delta). next delta → `252.96584104589149 + 0.00038742825540794 = ...` etc.
   198	- Result mz `[None, 252.96545361882283, 252.96584104589149, ...]`, zipped with intensity, drop the leading `(None,None)` → first real point `(252.96545361882283, 1328.2458)`.
   199	
   200	### Round-trip proof (decisive lossless test) — RAN IN SESSION
   201	Decoded the entire chunked `spectra_data` and compared the per-spectrum `(round(mz,6), intensity)` multiset to the point-layout `spectra_data` (both from the reference, same source):
   202	```
   203	chunked non-null total: 177742
   204	point   non-null total: 177742
   205	EXACT-match spectra: 14/14   mismatch: 0
   206	```
   207	[VERIFIED in session] This is the encode/decode contract the writer must reproduce.
   208	
   209	## Chunking Strategy
   210	
   211	### Decisions
   212	- **Window = fixed 50.0 m/z**, the reference default. [VERIFIED: `src/writer.rs:1217,1431` `ChunkingStrategy::Delta { chunk_size: 50.0 }`]
   213	- **Expose as a configurable option** (e.g. `--chunk-size`/CLI param) defaulting to 50.0, per CONTEXT discretion.
   214	- **One chunk row per NON-empty window**, ordered, per spectrum, in ascending m/z. Spectra appear in ascending `spectrum_index`; their chunks are contiguous and ordered. [VERIFIED: dump — spectrum 0 has 36 chunks, then spectrum 1, etc.; chunk rows grouped + ordered]
   215	- **`mz_chunk_start`/`end` = actual extent** (first/last non-null m/z in the window), confirmed above.
   216	
   217	### Windowing algorithm (mirror of `null_chunk_every_k`, `src/filter.rs:871`)
   218	Partition the per-spectrum (already sorted, already null-marked) m/z array into intervals each spanning ≤ `width` m/z:
   219	- `threshold = first_non_null_mz + width`.
   220	- Walk indices; when a non-null `mz[i] > threshold`, close the current chunk at `i` and advance `threshold` by `width` until `threshold >= mz[i]`.
   221	- Null pairs are skipped together (the loop steps past paired nulls so a chunk boundary never lands mid-null-pair).
   222	- **A length-1 chunk is avoided** (`if i - offset != 1`): the splitter won't emit a singleton chunk; it rolls the point into the adjacent chunk.
   223	- The final residual interval `[offset, n)` is always emitted.
   224	
   225	Note: because the threshold advances by `width` from the *first* m/z (not from fixed 50-m/z grid lines), chunk windows are anchored to the spectrum's m/z minimum, not to global 0/50/100 boundaries. Chunk widths are therefore "≤ 50 m/z from the chunk's own start," which is why `mz_chunk_end - mz_chunk_start` in the dump is ~40–50, variable. [VERIFIED: row 0 start=202.6 end=252.4 ≈ 49.8 span]
   226	
   227	### Pipeline order (per scan, before column build) — IMPORTANT
   228	1. Get sorted `(mz[], intensity[])` for the scan (already produced by the existing per-scan path).
   229	2. **Nullify zero-pairs:** compute `is_zero_pair_mask` over intensity; set the masked positions to null in **both** mz and intensity. (`is_zero_pair_mask`, `src/filter.rs:704`: position `i` is masked iff `intensity[i]==0` AND (previous was zero OR next is zero).)
   230	3. Partition with `null_chunk_every_k(mz, 50.0)`.
   231	4. For each interval: `mz_chunk_start/end` = first/last non-null mz; `mz_chunk_values` = `null_delta_encode(mz_slice)`; `intensity` list = `intensity_slice` (nullable); `chunk_encoding = "MS:1003089"`; `spectrum_index = ordinal`.
   232	5. Emit one chunk struct row per interval through the streaming Handle.
   233	
   234	## Don't Hand-Roll
   235	
   236	| Problem | Don't Build | Use Instead | Why |
   237	|---------|-------------|-------------|-----|
   238	| Rep/def levels for nullable list-of-scalar | Bespoke level arrays | Existing `MzPeakParquet.NestedLevels` + `ListOf(levels, hasValue)` | Already correct for list leaves (`data: list<byte>` aux array uses it); spike confirmed for double/float |
   239	| Streaming chunk rows to STORED zip | New writer | Phase-1 `Handle.WriteRowGroupAsync` + `AddStoredFromFile` | Chunk rows are just a different row unit; the seekable-temp-file path is unchanged |
   240	| Delta encode/decode | New numeric scheme | Mirror `null_delta_encode`/`null_delta_decode` byte-for-byte | The reference reader expects EXACTLY this null-aware scheme; any deviation breaks round-trip |
   241	| Window partitioning | Naive `floor(mz/50)` bucketing | Mirror `null_chunk_every_k` | Naive bucketing produces different chunk boundaries (global grid vs first-mz-anchored) and would not match the reference; also must skip null-pairs and avoid singleton chunks |
   242	
   243	**Key insight:** The reference's "delta" layout is not a plain consecutive-delta list. It is a *null-marked, zero-pair-suppressed, absolute-restart-after-null* scheme. Reproducing it faithfully is the entire difficulty of this phase; the Parquet plumbing is already solved.
   244	
   245	## Runtime State Inventory
   246	
   247	This is a code/format change, not a rename or data migration. No stored datastores, live-service config, OS-registered state, secrets/env vars, or build artifacts embed the renamed string.
   248	- **Stored data:** None — output archives are regenerated per run; no persistent store keyed on layout.
   249	- **Live service config:** None — no external service involved.
   250	- **OS-registered state:** None.
   251	- **Secrets/env vars:** None new (DOTNET_ROLL_FORWARD already used; unchanged).
   252	- **Build artifacts:** None beyond normal `bin/Release` rebuild.
   253	
   254	## Common Pitfalls
   255	
   256	### Pitfall 1: Assuming `mz_numpress_linear_bytes` must exist in delta mode
   257	**What goes wrong:** Adding an empty `list<uint8>` column to match the CONTEXT's struct sketch produces a 7-field struct that does NOT match the reference's 6-field struct.
   258	**Why it happens:** The CONTEXT struct sketch lists the Numpress column; the Rust source adds it only for NumpressLinear.
   259	**How to avoid:** Emit exactly 6 fields in delta mode. The Numpress column is a Phase-3 concern.
   260	**Warning signs:** pyarrow diff of our output vs reference shows an extra column.
   261	
   262	### Pitfall 2: Storing the start value as the first `mz_chunk_values` element
   263	**What goes wrong:** Off-by-one m/z reconstruction; first point doubled or shifted.
   264	**Why it happens:** A naive "first value + cumsum" reading. The reference stores deltas only; the start lives in `mz_chunk_start`.
   265	**How to avoid:** `mz_chunk_values` length == `len(mz_slice) - 1` (no leading null), or `== len(mz_slice)` only when a leading null is present. Decode starts from `mz_chunk_start`.
   266	**Warning signs:** Round-trip point count is `chunk_count + N` instead of equal.
   267	
   268	### Pitfall 3: Treating nulls as deltas (forgetting the absolute-restart rule)
   269	**What goes wrong:** After a null gap, applying the next value as a delta yields a wrong m/z.
   270	**Why it happens:** The encode stores the post-null value as an **absolute** m/z, not a delta.
   271	**How to avoid:** In encode, when `last is None` push the raw value; in decode, when `last is None` accept the value as absolute.
   272	**Warning signs:** Decoded m/z jumps to ~0 or ~original after every gap.
   273	
   274	### Pitfall 4: Naive `floor(mz/50)` windowing
   275	**What goes wrong:** Different chunk boundaries than the reference; singleton chunks; boundaries inside null-pairs.
   276	**Why it happens:** The reference anchors windows to the first m/z and advances the threshold; it also skips null-pairs and avoids length-1 chunks.
   277	**How to avoid:** Mirror `null_chunk_every_k`. (Round-trip still passes regardless of boundary choice as long as decode is inverse of encode — but matching the reference avoids a pyarrow schema/shape diff and future surprises.)
   278	
   279	### Pitfall 5: large_list expectation
   280	**What goes wrong:** A test asserting `large_list` fails because Parquet.Net emits `list`.
   281	**How to avoid:** Assert on item *type* (double/float) and on round-trip values, not on the list-offset width. The validator and Python reader accept both.
   282	
   283	## Code Examples
   284	
   285	### Verified Parquet.Net list-of-scalar column build (from the live spike)
   286	```csharp
   287	// schema leaf path is "chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item" (note the "/list/" segment)
   288	var fVal = (DataField)schema.GetDataFields().First(f => f.Path.ToString() == "chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item");
   289	var fInt = (DataField)schema.GetDataFields().First(f => f.Path.ToString() == "chunk/intensity/list/item");
   290	// spike measured: list item MaxDefinitionLevel = 4, MaxRepetitionLevel = 1
   291	
   292	// Per chunk row, build LeafRow entries with the existing helpers:
   293	//   present item   -> def = MaxDefinitionLevel        (4)
   294	//   null  item     -> def = MaxDefinitionLevel - 1    (3)
   295	//   rep            -> 0 for the first item of the row's list, MaxRepetitionLevel (1) thereafter
   296	int vP = fVal.MaxDefinitionLevel, vN = fVal.MaxDefinitionLevel - 1, vRep = fVal.MaxRepetitionLevel;
   297	// row whose mz_chunk_values == [delta, null, delta]:
   298	var row = MzPeakParquet.ListOf(new[]{vP, vN, vP}, new[]{true, false, true});
   299	// NestedLevels(fVal, rows) -> (defLevels, repLevels); only NON-null values go in the value Array.
   300	var (def, rep) = MzPeakParquet.NestedLevels(fVal, rows);
   301	await rg.WriteColumnAsync(new DataColumn(fVal, nonNullDoubleValues, def, rep));
   302	```
   303	Spike round-trip output (values correct, nulls preserved):
   304	```
   305	chunk/mz_chunk_values/list/item = [0.1, null, 0.3, null, 250]
   306	chunk/intensity/list/item       = [10, 20, 30, null, 99]
   307	```
   308	[VERIFIED: ran on Parquet.Net 5.0.1, net via DOTNET_ROLL_FORWARD, arch -arm64]
   309	
   310	**Streaming carries it unchanged:** the existing `Handle.WriteRowGroupAsync(schema, cols)` writes each `schema.GetDataFields()` leaf from the `cols` dictionary. List leaves are ordinary `DataField`s in that walk; no Handle change is required. The new facet stream mirrors `PointFacetStream` (buffer per scan → flush at `Cap` → `Close(finalMetadata)`), differing only in that one chunk *row* carries variable-length lists (so the cap counts chunk rows, not points). **Gotcha vs point columns:** point columns are flat (def/rep = null); chunk list columns MUST pass computed `def`/`rep` arrays. Also the value Array passed to `DataColumn` contains only the non-null elements (nulls are expressed purely via def-levels), exactly as the aux-array `data` list already does.
   311	
   312	## array_index Footer Delta
   313	
   314	### Decisions
   315	- Chunked `spectrum_array_index` has **5 entries** (one per non-index chunk field), prefix `"chunk"`. [VERIFIED: footer dump]
   316	- m/z entries carry `transform: "MS:1003901"`; intensity carries `transform: "MS:1003902"`. The v1 point footer in our writer currently OMITS `transform` (and still validates) — for chunked, **include the transform CURIEs** to match the reference and to register the delta/null-marking transform. [VERIFIED: footer dump; `transform` is NOT in the array_index.json `required` list, so it is additive-safe]
   317	- `sorting_rank: 0` on all four m/z entries; **`sorting_rank: null` (omit) on the intensity entry** — matches both the reference chunk footer and the v1 point footer. [VERIFIED: footer dump]
   318	- Register the new CURIEs in `cv_list`: `MS:1003089` (delta encoding), `MS:1003901` (m/z transform), `MS:1003902` (intensity transform), plus the existing `MS:1000514/MS:1000523/MS:1000040/MS:1000515/MS:1000521/MS:1000131`. The v1 cv_list machinery (`CollectPrefix`) must see these so cv_list stays exhaustive. [CITED: CONTEXT "cv_list stays exhaustive (any new transform/encoding CURIE registered)"]
